textArray: Argentina's world cup began|in disastrous fashion as|they surrendered an early|lead to  lose to Saudi Arabia
The bookies' confidence in|Argentina hit its lowest point|as they struggled to make|a breakthrough against Mexico
Argentina were seemingly cruising|into the quarter-finals after a Messi|penalty doubled their lead, but then…
…the Netherlands' switch to "route one" football|shifted the momentum of the tie, and|the Dutch equalised in the dying minutes
With a two-goal lead and Argentina|in complete control, bookmakers gave|them a +90% chance of victory
Two Mbappe goals in just|95 seconds sunk Argentina's|chances back to 50%, exactly|where they were at the|beginning of the game
Extra-time goals for Messi|and then Mbappe sent Argentina's|odds yo-yoing once more
Despite qualifying from their group with|two wins, bookmakers remained unconvinced|that Australia were a serious threat to win it all.| Their odds peaked at just 0.4%.
Australia's odds increased after they|took a shock early lead in their opening|game against France, but it was not to last
Bookmakers downgraded Belguim's|chances of winning the World|Cup in the months leading|up to the tournament
Despite winning their opening game|Belguim's odds fell due to their|lackluster performance
Belgium's chances fell further following|Romain Saiss's goal for Morocco. Defeat left|Belgium needing to win their final|group game to progress
Belgium had many chances to take|the lead against Croatia but could|not convert, resulting in an early exit
Brazil's were favourties on the|eve of the tournament
Brazil's odds increased by 3 points|after shock results in Group E|ensured they would not have to play|Spain or Germany in the quarter-finals
The chances of Brazil winning it all|drifted as they failed to score against|Croatia in 90 minutes
Brazil's odds peaked after|Neymar's extra time goal…
…but with minutes left, Croatia equalised|with their first shot on target, taking|the game to penalties
Cameroon's odds briefly jumped when they opened|the scoring against Serbia, but they would then|concede two quick goals just before half time
A late winner against favourites Brazil was|not enough to see Cameroon qualify for|the knockout stages due to Switzerland's|win against Serbia
Canada's odds increased slightly as|they dominated the first half against|Belgium. By the final whistle, the North|American side had attempted 22|shots but failed to score
Alphonso Davies' early goal gave Canada|the lead against Croatia, giving them|real hope of escaping the group
With two defeats, Canada were one of|the few nations to be eliminated before|their final group game. Ultimately,|Morocco also proved too tough a task|for the Canadians
When Costa Rica took the lead against Germany|they were briefly on course to qualify from|Group E alongside Japan
Despite reaching the final in 2018,|bookies viewed Croatia as a long shot|to win in Qatar
Croatia's odds dipped after they conceded|to Canada, putting them at risk|of securing just a single point from their|opening two games
Perisic's equaliser boosted|Croatia's title chances
Even after Croatia reached the quarter|finals, bookmakers gave them just|a 1 in 50 chance of winning|the World Cup
Petkovic's equaliser against Brazil|came in the 117th minute, giving|Croatia the momentum as the|game headed to penalties
Croatia started well in their semi-final|and their title odds peaked at 13%|in the moments before Argentina's|opening goal
On the eve of their first game Denmark|had better title odds than Morocco,|Croatia and Japan combined
Denmark looked set to secure a second|consecutive draw, until a late Mbappe|winner left the Danes requiring|a victory in their final group game
Australia's goal sunk the Danes, putting|an end to their disappointing tournament
Ecuador's equaliser against the Netherlands|increased their title chances
Ecuador only needed a draw|against Senegal to qualify. In the|67th minute they equalised through|Moises Caicedo, but conceded once|more leaving their odds unchanged
England's title odds fell before the|tournament due to poor results|in the nations league
After improving following a convincing|victory over Iran, England's odds decreased|during a shaky performance against the USA
Morocco's shock win against Portugal|improved both England and France's|odds, since it was viewed as giving|them an easier potential semi-final
Every top team saw their|chances increase once Brazil|were eliminated by Croatia
Tchouameni's long range strike|gave France the early advantage
Following Kane's equaliser from the penalty spot England|looked more threatening that France, which was|reflected in their title chances surpassing their pre-game
There was too little time between the|penalty award and Kane's miss for|changes in odds to be detected
France's chances of defending their title fell|slightly before the World Cup began as news|came out that Benzema would join Pogba| and Kante in missing the tournament
France's odds improved following|Portugal's elimination to Morocco
After Kane equalised for|England, France's title odds|fell to 23%, exactly equal|to their opponents chances
As the final began bookmakers assessed the contest as a coin toss,|both France and Argentina were given 50% chances of victory
Following Argentina's second goal,|France's odds fell below 10%. It looked|as though they were dead and buried
France's odds peaked just|above 50% after Mbappe's|two goals in 95 seconds,|and as both teams frantically|searched for a winner at|the end of normal time
Germany's title odds crashed after they|conceded two late goals to lose to Japan
Germany's odds fell further after Spain|thrashed Costa Rica 7-0. Spain's superior goal|difference meant Germany could be eliminated|even with wins in both their remaining games

Germany were preparing for a must-win game|against Spain, but then Costa Rica's surprise|win over Japan altered the permutations of|Group E, meaning a draw against Spain and|a win in their final group game would likely|be enough for Germany to qualify
Even while trailing against|Spain, Germany's title odds|remained above 4%, with the|possibility of a three-way tie|for second in the group
Following early goals for Germany against Costa Rica|and Spain against Japan, Germany's title chances|improved to exceed their pre-tournament level
But two quick goals for Japan|suddenly left Germany on equal points|with Spain and going out on goal difference
Ghana's odds fell when they surrendered|a two-goal lead against South Korea but|recovered once they retook the lead with|a Kudus goal minutes later
Ghana needed to avoid defeat|against Uruguay, a team who|eliminated them with help from|a Luis Suarez handball in 2010
A well-deserved late winner against Wales|put Iran in pole position to qualify from|Group C alongside England
Iran's chances fell after the USA took the lead|in their final group game. Despite some close|chances late on, Iran could not find the|moment of quality needed to equalise

Iran's moment of the tournament arguably occurred before|they kicked a ball. Prior to their first group game, the Iranian|team remained silent during their national anthem, seen| as a brave act of solidarity with protestors back home.
Two late Japan goals secured|them a surprise victory over|Germany in their opening game
Japan's strong position in Group E crumbled as|they conceded a late goal against Costa Rica
Japan were on the verge of|elimination after conceding an|early goal against Spain| in their final group game

Throughout the World Cup, Japan relied on super subs at half-time| to shift momentum and create attacking opportunities. This was the|case against Spain, where a strike from Doan and then a stretching|toe to rescue the ball from the very edge of the pitch by Mitoma -| both substitutes - turned the game in Japan's favour

Even when they took the lead against Croatia, bookmakers|remained pessimistic about Japan's chances of defeating| the likes of Brazil and Argentina if they progressed, with their|probability of winning the World Cup peaking at just over 2%.
Messi broke the deadlock for Argentina,|reducing Mexico's chances of advancing

Leading in their final group game, Mexico needed to score an|additional goal or for Argentina to extend their lead against|Poland to qualify. Both sides missed a littany of chances,|ending Mexico's streak of reaching the knockout stages|at seven consecutive world cups
Morocco started the tournament with just|a 0.3% chance of winning having|replaced their manager in September
Two late goals sealed Morocco's victory|over Belgium and left them well|placed to reach the knockout stage
Morocco's title odds gradually improved as|Spain failed to break down their tough defence|and the game crept towards penalties
The bookmakers doubled Morcco's title|chances following En-Nesyri's towering|header for the opening goal
After conceding an early goal to France,|Morocco's odds actually improved slightly|as they created the better chances
Morocco's odds decreased due to|Argentina, viewed as the stronger team,|defeating Croatia in the other semi-final
The Netherlands' odds of winning the|World Cup jumped sharply after Croatia|upset Brazil in the other quarter-final
Late in their quarter-final, the Netherlands' title odds fell to just 1%
Two late goals by substitute Wout|Weghorst, including one from a|deceptive free kick routine,|brought the Netherlands level
In the run up to their last 16 game, the|Netherlands' odds fell as consensus|developed that their opponents|the USA were the more fluent|and dynamic team
In their final group game, Poland's odds fell as an additional|goal for either Argentina or Mexico, who were both|dominating their respective games, would have|eliminated the European side
Poland's odds were gradually|drifting until they opened|account against Saudi Arabia
Portugal's odds jumped following|Morocco's win over Spain

Portugal's manager Fernando Santos made the bold|call to start their first knockout match with Cristiano|Ronaldo on the bench, and the decision paid off with|his replacement, Goncalo Ramos, scoring a hat-trick
Brazil's surprise exit in the quarter-finals increased|Portugal's title chances from 13% to 17%
Bookies lowered Portugal's chances|of winning the World Cup to one|in 10 after Morocco's goal. From|then on, there odds gradually|fell as they failed to find a way|through the Moroccan defence
After the winning the Asian Cup in 2019, Qatar entered|the World Cup with a better chance of winning|than five other nations - Australia, Costa Rica,|Iran, Saudi Arabia and Tunisia
Qatar were one of just|two teams to be eliminated|before the final group game
Saudi Arabia's odds of winning| the World Cup only increased slightly|after their win against Argentina
Saudi Arabia were one of three|teams to win their opening game but|fail to qualify for the knockout stage,|the others being Ecuador and Belgium
Despite being just four wins away|from a Wold Cup title, bookies|gave Senegal just a 0.7% chance
Senegal's title odds fell in the weeks|leading up to their first game due to|the injury of star player Sadio Mane
Serbia's odds were rising gradually|until Richarlison scored his first|of two goals for Brazil
Serbia's probability of winning the World Cup|shifted from 0.5% to 0.9% in a matter of minutes,| when they scored twice in first half extra| time to take the lead
Winning 3-1, Serbia conceded two quick|goals to leave them needing a|win against Switzerland to qualify
Serbia once again surrendered a lead|in their final group game, and their|odds drifted as they searched|for an equaliser in vain

South Korea's chances had been gradually trending|down throughout the entire group stage, but|then a goal by Hwang Hee-chan, completely|against the run of the play, gave them the|lead against Portugal and a spot in the last 16
South Korea briefly looked well placed|to qualify from Group H after two quick|goals from Cho Gue-sung gave them|the lead against Ghana
Bookmakers increased Spain's title chances|from 9% to 11% following their dominant|opening game performance
Spain's title odds peaked at 13%|after they scored the opening|goal against Germany

Peculiarly, Spain's odds actually improved towards the end of|their shock defeat to Japan. The loss meant Spain finished|second in the group and would therefore avoided Croatia|in the last 16 and favourites Brazil in the quarters.
Spain's odds kept falling as their last 16|contest with Morocco headed for penalties
Switzerland's odds jumped following Spain's| elimination,since Morocco were viewed|as an easier potential quarter-final match up
Switzerland needed a draw in their final group game| to reach the knockout stages, and were trailing until|goals either side of half-time gave them the lead

Tunisia did not score a goal in the World Cup|until the 58th minute of their 3rd game,|but that goal meant that if Denmark|equalised against Australia, Tunisia|would have qualified for the knockout stage
Group D was viewed as one of the least|competitve groups, with both Tunisia|and Australia among the teams with the|lowest chances of winning the World Cup
Uruguay's title odds fell following their|opening game, as bookmakers reflected|on their unconvincing performance

Assuming South Korea failed to defeat|Portugal, Uruguay simply needed to beat|Ghana to reach the knockout stages. With Portugal|taking an early lead and de Arrascaeta giving|Uruguay a two goal advantage, prospects were|looking good for the South American side

But with minutes left South Korea took the lead against Portugal,|meaning Uruguay needed one more goal to progress on goal|difference. With some of their best attacking players already|substituted, Uruguay could not find that crucial 3rd goal
The USA's title odds fell after they conceded|an equaliser to Wales in their opening game
USA's odds peaked just above 1%|prior to their last 16 match up

Wales were on the brink of elimination going into their|final group game - they needed to defeat England|by seven goals or, more realistically, beat England|and rely on a draw between the USA and Iran
Wales' odds bounced back when Gareth|Bale scored a late penalty to|equalise against the USA
